WEBVTT

00:01.292 --> 00:05.755
♪ ♪

00:36.202 --> 00:40.540
♪ ♪

01:09.360 --> 01:15.074
♪ ♪

01:35.845 --> 01:41.518
♪ Happy birthday to you,
happy birthday to you ♪

01:41.601 --> 01:44.854
♪ Happy birthday, dear Dylan ♪

01:44.938 --> 01:46.856
♪ You son-of-a-gun
of a wonderful guy... ♪

01:46.940 --> 01:47.690
{\an3}Will you guys
just stop singing

01:47.774 --> 01:49.651
{\an3}if I blow out
the candles, please?

01:49.734 --> 01:50.944
♪ Happy birthday to you. ♪

01:51.027 --> 01:52.487
Okay, make a wish.

01:52.570 --> 01:54.197
(coughing)

01:54.280 --> 01:55.865
Hay, all right.

01:55.949 --> 01:58.368
Thanks, everybody, for coming.

01:58.451 --> 02:00.370
(coughing)

02:00.453 --> 02:02.247
{\an1}What he would like
to say is that although

02:02.330 --> 02:05.333
this is not the actual
date until next week,

02:05.416 --> 02:06.376
{\an1}he's very glad that
you could all be here

02:06.459 --> 02:09.086
{\an1}to celebrate his,
what, 80th...?

02:09.169 --> 02:11.214
Oh.<i> 18th</i> birthday.

02:11.297 --> 02:13.716
Well, I'm glad
I'm not the only one anymore.

02:13.800 --> 02:14.384
That's quite a cough
you got there, bro.

02:14.467 --> 02:16.886
I've been practicing.

02:16.970 --> 02:18.388
{\an1}(music playing)
Oh, I love this song.

02:22.600 --> 02:24.727
Come on.
No.

02:24.811 --> 02:26.396
Come on!
No.

02:32.318 --> 02:33.236
Mr. Meyers?

02:33.319 --> 02:36.072
Gil.

02:36.155 --> 02:39.367
{\an5}Gil, can I ask you
about my paper
on Emily Dickinson?

02:39.450 --> 02:41.286
Come on, Andrea.
That's business.

02:41.369 --> 02:42.370
I'm off duty tonight.

02:42.453 --> 02:44.747
Why did you give me a B+?

02:44.831 --> 02:45.415
You don't let up, do you?

02:45.498 --> 02:47.959
It's a party!

02:49.460 --> 02:53.381
♪ Whatcha gonna do
when she catches you? ♪

02:53.464 --> 02:55.758
♪<i> Ah, ah, ah, ah</i> ♪

02:55.842 --> 02:58.344
♪ Only you, this time
I saw you at the club. ♪

02:58.428 --> 03:02.390
(music ends, clapping)

03:02.473 --> 03:06.436
{\an3}Where did you learn to dance
like that, anyway, huh?

03:06.519 --> 03:07.395
Completely self-taught.

03:07.478 --> 03:09.772
Yeah?
That's what they all say.

03:09.856 --> 03:10.940
What else do they say?

03:11.024 --> 03:14.819
You ordered the onion rings,
I ordered the French fries.

03:14.903 --> 03:17.447
{\an3}Oh, yeah. I got
your order down here.

03:17.530 --> 03:20.325
{\an1}Hey! What are
you doing here?

03:20.408 --> 03:23.077
Hanging out. Want some cake?

03:23.161 --> 03:24.454
No. You know, what I do want

03:24.537 --> 03:27.332
is to know what I have to do
to get a decent grade from you.

03:27.415 --> 03:31.794
Take my clothes off?

03:31.878 --> 03:33.755
Uh... Andrea, do you know Sue?

03:33.838 --> 03:36.633
{\an1}Uh... No.
Not really.

03:36.716 --> 03:38.801
{\an3}Andrea Zuckerman,
Sue Scanlon.

03:38.885 --> 03:39.802
Hi.

03:39.886 --> 03:40.845
Hi.

03:40.929 --> 03:42.305
Listen, Gil, I'm not kidding.

03:42.388 --> 03:44.515
My mom's going to kill me
if I fail freshman English.

03:44.599 --> 03:45.600
{\an3}Sue...

03:45.683 --> 03:47.143
{\an1}Look, I'll just
leave you two

03:47.226 --> 03:51.314
{\an1}to, uh...
take care of business.

03:51.397 --> 03:53.107
Sue, it's hard to
get decent grades

03:53.191 --> 03:54.359
{\an3}if you're cutting
class all the time.

03:54.442 --> 03:55.777
Well, couldn't I just

03:55.860 --> 03:57.779
do an independent
study project instead?

03:57.862 --> 04:00.657
I mean, I really
do work better one-on-one.

04:00.740 --> 04:02.325
Tell you what.

04:02.408 --> 04:04.327
Come by tomorrow,

04:04.410 --> 04:06.162
{\an1}and we'll talk
about it.

04:06.245 --> 04:08.748
And don't let your
mom get you down.

04:08.831 --> 04:10.249
{\an1}SUE:
See ya.

04:22.720 --> 04:24.889
You're late.

04:24.973 --> 04:25.348
Only by four minutes

04:25.431 --> 04:27.850
and 13 seconds.

04:27.934 --> 04:29.644
Are you making fun of me?

04:29.727 --> 04:31.354
No.

04:31.437 --> 04:33.815
You can forget about going out
for the rest of the week.

04:33.898 --> 04:35.400
{\an3}And next week, too,
for that matter.

04:35.483 --> 04:36.609
But, Mom, you said I could...

04:36.693 --> 04:38.027
Uncle Henry is coming tomorrow.

04:38.111 --> 04:38.611
He'll be sleeping here
in Scotty's room.

04:41.948 --> 04:42.490
Well, why can't he stay

04:42.573 --> 04:46.828
downstairs
in the den?

04:46.911 --> 04:48.579
Mom, you haven't let anybody
touch this room

04:48.663 --> 04:51.040
for a whole year.
I mean, not since Scotty died.

04:51.124 --> 04:52.041
Excuse me, Sue Scanlon.

04:52.125 --> 04:52.959
When you have a family
and a home

04:53.042 --> 04:54.544
{\an3}of your own, you can
decide who sleeps where.

04:54.627 --> 04:57.505
It's only fitting that
Henry should stay here.

04:57.588 --> 05:00.341
He was Scotty's favorite uncle.

05:00.425 --> 05:01.509
(door closes)

05:06.931 --> 05:08.975
I thought Office Service
was supposed to be fun.

05:09.058 --> 05:10.685
{\an1}You get to know
who's coming in late

05:10.768 --> 05:12.395
and who's flunking out.

05:12.478 --> 05:14.731
{\an3}Mostly I just deliver
notes for Mrs. Teasley.

05:14.814 --> 05:16.566
What's Sue in for?

05:16.649 --> 05:19.527
{\an3}She practically
lives here.

05:19.610 --> 05:22.071
Hi, Sue.
Hi.

05:22.155 --> 05:24.407
All right, I have
to go pick up the attendance.

05:24.490 --> 05:26.909
{\an6}Well, wait. Where do I
put the announcements
for the Art Fair?

05:26.993 --> 05:28.453
{\an1}Just put it with
all the other folders,

05:28.536 --> 05:29.454
and don't peek in the files.

05:36.335 --> 05:39.422
Listen, Sue,
we never got a chance to talk

05:39.505 --> 05:40.590
about what happened
between you and David

05:40.673 --> 05:41.716
at the dance last week.

05:41.799 --> 05:42.592
You don't have to worry, Donna.

05:42.675 --> 05:44.886
He doesn't mean anything to me.

05:44.969 --> 05:47.096
I know you don't mean that.

05:47.180 --> 05:50.767
I don't want you to have
to feel weird around David now.

05:50.850 --> 05:52.477
Look, I told you
I'd stay away from him.

05:52.560 --> 05:55.688
You don't have to do that.

05:55.772 --> 05:58.107
Look, Sue,
David does care about you.

05:58.191 --> 05:59.984
But there is
a difference

06:00.068 --> 06:01.944
between romantic love
and affection shown

06:02.028 --> 06:04.447
from a friend who's almost
like part of your family.

06:04.530 --> 06:05.948
I know that, Donna.

06:06.032 --> 06:08.367
I know all about it. Okay?

06:09.619 --> 06:10.995
{\an1}Now, hold it
just a moment.

06:11.079 --> 06:12.330
I'm in shock here.

06:12.413 --> 06:13.956
Brandon is coming
to a dance club?

06:14.040 --> 06:15.291
Like, to have fun?

06:15.375 --> 06:16.459
{\an3}Oh, he's
been practicing.

06:16.542 --> 06:17.502
And he's going to
show you guys up.

06:17.585 --> 06:20.630
Kingston 12,
here we come!

06:20.713 --> 06:22.131
I haven't been.

06:22.215 --> 06:23.591
I have no idea what
she's talking about.

06:23.674 --> 06:25.301
{\an1}Kingston 12?
You're kidding, right?

06:25.384 --> 06:26.302
Good luck, Baryshnikov.

06:26.385 --> 06:29.555
Can't wait to compare moves
with you, big guy.

06:32.225 --> 06:33.518
Brandon, could it be

06:33.601 --> 06:37.522
{\an1}that you're becoming
open-minded in your old age?

06:37.605 --> 06:39.482
{\an3}More like
feebleminded, Bren.

06:39.565 --> 06:42.151
What am I thinking about?

06:42.235 --> 06:43.486
I hate dancing.

06:43.569 --> 06:44.821
Nikki likes it.

06:44.904 --> 06:45.947
Yeah.

06:46.030 --> 06:47.615
So, you and Dylan
want to come with?

06:47.698 --> 06:50.827
{\an1}It looks doubtful,
at the rate he's going.

06:50.910 --> 06:51.702
{\an1}You know, I'm really
worried about him.

06:51.786 --> 06:53.830
What did the doctor say?

06:53.913 --> 06:54.664
{\an3}You know how you
feel about dancing?

06:54.747 --> 06:56.791
{\an3}That's how he feels
about doctors.

06:56.874 --> 06:57.500
(coughing)

06:57.583 --> 06:59.502
{\an1}Hey, D,
how's that cough?

06:59.585 --> 07:01.587
It's all right.

07:01.671 --> 07:03.548
How you doing?

07:03.631 --> 07:05.591
{\an3}(coughing)

07:05.675 --> 07:09.387
{\an5}SUE:
I don't get why
Mrs. Teasley hates me.

07:09.470 --> 07:10.555
I mean, what did I do to her?

07:10.638 --> 07:13.391
I begged her
not to call my mother,

07:13.474 --> 07:15.184
{\an1}but she said
that she has to.

07:15.268 --> 07:15.726
{\an3}You're really going
through a tough patch

07:15.810 --> 07:18.354
right now, aren't you?

07:18.437 --> 07:20.648
I mean, so what
if I flunk out?

07:20.731 --> 07:22.942
My mom would
probably die of shame.

07:23.025 --> 07:25.236
{\an1}She thinks her
daughter's a deadbeat.

07:25.319 --> 07:26.195
{\an3}Do you think
you're a deadbeat?

07:26.279 --> 07:28.698
Sometimes I just think
I'd be better off dead.

07:28.781 --> 07:29.699
I mean, it should have been me,

07:29.782 --> 07:31.534
not my brother.

07:31.617 --> 07:34.370
I'm sorry.

07:34.453 --> 07:37.498
For what? For being honest?

07:37.582 --> 07:40.042
We all get down
on ourselves sometimes,

07:40.126 --> 07:40.710
but you get through it.

07:40.793 --> 07:42.712
You've just
got to focus

07:42.795 --> 07:43.713
{\an3}on the good things
in your life.

07:43.796 --> 07:46.382
{\an3}The things that are
worth sticking around for.

07:46.465 --> 07:49.719
Like what? There's nothing.

07:49.802 --> 07:51.554
Well...

07:51.637 --> 07:54.682
if you weren't around,
you wouldn't know me.

07:54.765 --> 07:55.600
See what you would

07:55.683 --> 07:58.436
be missing out on?

07:58.519 --> 07:59.896
Are you conceited or what?

07:59.979 --> 08:01.939
Of course I am.

08:02.023 --> 08:03.399
Did I detect a smile there?

08:03.482 --> 08:06.402
Hmm? Almost?

08:06.485 --> 08:09.739
I came here to talk
about grades and papers.

08:09.822 --> 08:11.782
Here you are,
trying to cheer me up.

08:13.826 --> 08:15.786
You really are different.

08:15.870 --> 08:18.998
So are you.

08:19.081 --> 08:22.210
Sue, you're a very special girl.

08:22.293 --> 08:24.253
You just need
to believe it.

08:44.690 --> 08:46.442
GIL:
<i>What do the works</i>

08:46.525 --> 08:49.111
of Poe, Hawthorne and Crane
have in common?

08:49.195 --> 08:51.489
Can anyone tell me?

08:51.572 --> 08:52.657
{\an3}Brandon?

08:52.740 --> 08:57.620
Uh... Well,
they're all very... dark,

08:57.703 --> 09:00.248
{\an1}for lack
of a better word.

09:00.331 --> 09:01.832
No, that's exactly
the right word.

09:01.916 --> 09:04.460
And they all rely heavily
on symbolism

09:04.543 --> 09:07.088
as they explore
the dark side of humanity.

09:07.171 --> 09:09.507
Mr. Meyers.

09:09.590 --> 09:11.592
Thank you, Ms. Walsh.
Uh... Mrs. Teasley

09:11.676 --> 09:13.469
{\an6}said you should
look at it as
soon as possible.

09:13.552 --> 09:16.264
Excuse me. We're trying
to learn something here.

09:16.347 --> 09:17.765
I doubt that, Brandon.

09:24.605 --> 09:28.526
Um... Where were we?

09:28.609 --> 09:30.486
On the dark side.

09:31.904 --> 09:33.823
I don't get it.

09:33.906 --> 09:34.824
First, he bails
in the middle of AP,

09:34.907 --> 09:38.119
and then he's a no-show
for the staff meeting.

09:38.202 --> 09:40.621
It's just very
out of character for Gil.

09:40.705 --> 09:41.831
{\an1}Is it?

09:41.914 --> 09:43.624
You don't think so?

09:43.708 --> 09:46.168
{\an6}Let's just say,
the more I get
to know Mr. Meyers,

09:46.252 --> 09:48.629
{\an3}the less about
him surprises me.

09:48.713 --> 09:51.007
So, Brandon, when do you want
to get together and do...?

09:51.090 --> 09:52.466
{\an1}The meeting. The meeting
that we're having.

09:52.550 --> 09:53.634
Right. The meeting.

09:53.718 --> 09:54.510
What meeting?

09:54.593 --> 09:56.178
{\an1}Uh... Well, it's
a very private meeting.

09:56.262 --> 09:57.346
It's a guy thing.

09:57.430 --> 09:58.681
Would you excuse us?

09:58.764 --> 10:00.308
How's Friday?

10:00.391 --> 10:02.143
That doesn't give you
much time to practice.

10:02.226 --> 10:02.893
Silver, you told me
you could teach me

10:02.977 --> 10:05.521
{\an1}how to dance
in one session.

10:05.604 --> 10:07.857
Did I say that?

10:07.940 --> 10:10.526
{\an3}Oh, my God! You're right.
He's burning up!

10:10.609 --> 10:11.569
Okay, so I'll go home.

10:11.652 --> 10:13.404
I'll watch some videos,
drink some chicken soup.

10:13.487 --> 10:15.531
{\an1}The only place you're
going is to the doctor's.

10:15.615 --> 10:16.490
{\an3}Brenda....
Dylan,

10:16.574 --> 10:18.409
stop being so macho.

10:19.410 --> 10:21.704
Now, even if you feel better
in a day or two,

10:21.787 --> 10:23.372
I want you to finish
the whole prescription.

10:23.456 --> 10:24.707
Thanks, Doc. I will.

10:24.790 --> 10:27.668
Good to see you, Dylan.

10:27.752 --> 10:29.378
And happy birthday.

10:29.462 --> 10:30.755
{\an1}Yeah, I bet you never thought
I'd make it to 18, huh?

10:30.838 --> 10:32.882
{\an3}I was afraid you wouldn't
make it to eight.

10:32.965 --> 10:36.510
{\an6}Have you been in
any more motorcycle
accidents recently?

10:36.594 --> 10:39.221
No, but I did bruise
some ribs surfing last year.

10:39.305 --> 10:42.308
Surfing? Where? Santa Monica?

10:42.391 --> 10:44.560
No, no. There are no waves
there anymore.

10:44.644 --> 10:46.520
(coughing)

10:46.604 --> 10:49.398
Mostly, I go up to Malibu
'cause the water's cleaner.

10:49.482 --> 10:51.901
Look, Dylan,
don't fool yourself.

10:51.984 --> 10:54.070
You have to read the signs.

10:54.153 --> 10:56.280
After a big rain,
you can find all sorts

10:56.364 --> 10:58.407
of nasty bacteria
in the channel.

10:58.491 --> 11:00.868
Oh, yeah. But, Doc, when you see
a four-foot set rolling in,

11:00.951 --> 11:02.953
it's kind of hard
to stay out of the water.

11:03.037 --> 11:04.914
{\an3}Look, Dylan,
do yourself a favor.

11:04.997 --> 11:08.751
{\an3}Try some indoor
sports for a change.

11:08.834 --> 11:12.463
(coughing)

11:12.546 --> 11:14.548
DAVID:
That's it for today, kiddies.

11:14.632 --> 11:16.425
And for those of you thinking
of cutting classes, remember,

11:16.509 --> 11:19.929
don't do the crime
if you can't do the time.

11:20.012 --> 11:22.306
All right. I'll tell
you what I find out.

11:22.390 --> 11:23.432
{\an3}Okay.
How you doing, man?

11:23.516 --> 11:24.266
{\an1}Doing good.
How you doing?

11:24.350 --> 11:25.935
{\an3}All right.

11:26.018 --> 11:28.229
AP English just isn't
interesting without Meyers here.

11:28.312 --> 11:29.271
I hope he's all right.

11:29.355 --> 11:30.773
He's been gone
since Tuesday.

11:30.856 --> 11:31.774
{\an3}Checked on him
at home?

11:31.857 --> 11:33.275
{\an1}Nah. His machine's on
all the time.

11:33.359 --> 11:35.236
{\an1}That reminds me.
I was going to ask you.

11:35.319 --> 11:36.904
Do you know where
4580 Malibu Coast Drive is?

11:36.987 --> 11:38.906
{\an1}Uh... yeah. It's
right by where I surf.

11:38.989 --> 11:39.907
Why? What's up there?

11:39.990 --> 11:41.951
That's where Gil lives.

11:42.034 --> 11:44.078
{\an3}I thought I might
stop in say hi, you know.

11:44.161 --> 11:45.955
Oh, yeah.
That's a great place to live.

11:46.038 --> 11:47.039
And I miss those waves.

11:47.123 --> 11:50.292
Strep throat's gnarly stuff.
You look better though.

11:50.376 --> 11:51.502
You know, I hate to admit it,

11:51.585 --> 11:52.837
but antibiotics,
they work sometimes.

11:52.920 --> 11:53.963
{\an3}Well, you know, four out of
five doctors surveyed....

11:54.046 --> 11:56.340
Hey, you guys,
I've got some bad news.

11:56.424 --> 11:57.466
Gil Meyers is in big trouble.

11:57.550 --> 11:58.801
What do you mean?

11:58.884 --> 12:00.136
Well, you know how he likes

12:00.219 --> 12:01.429
to flirt with all the girls?

12:01.512 --> 12:03.639
Yeah.
Yeah.

12:03.722 --> 12:04.849
Well, this time he may have
taken it too far.

12:04.932 --> 12:07.476
I don't know all the details,

12:07.560 --> 12:08.144
but he's been
"relieved of his duties

12:08.227 --> 12:09.812
pending an investigation",

12:09.895 --> 12:10.980
quote unquote.

12:11.063 --> 12:13.482
What kind of investigation?

12:13.566 --> 12:16.735
For "sexual misconduct
with a female student".

12:27.413 --> 12:28.664
When'd the doc say

12:28.747 --> 12:30.166
you could get back
in the water, man?

12:30.249 --> 12:31.459
I don't know.

12:31.542 --> 12:33.169
{\an1}Man, looks like
a killer set coming in.

12:33.252 --> 12:34.837
Yes, I know!

12:34.920 --> 12:36.005
Brandon, would you look
at that water?

12:36.088 --> 12:37.673
Have you ever seen anything
more beautiful?

12:37.756 --> 12:39.008
{\an1}I'm gonna go knock
on Meyers' door.

12:39.091 --> 12:40.009
You gonna be all right?

12:40.092 --> 12:41.469
Yeah, I'm just
gonna hang out.

12:41.552 --> 12:42.553
{\an1}Cool.

12:45.139 --> 12:47.641
MEYERS:
<i>So, the subs aren't cutting it?</i>

12:47.725 --> 12:48.976
Well, let's just say

12:49.059 --> 12:52.021
these people aren't
AP English teachers.

12:52.104 --> 12:53.647
Fourth-grade math maybe.

12:53.731 --> 12:56.150
{\an3}(chuckles):
I'm sorry about that.

12:56.233 --> 12:57.902
{\an1}I hope they find
someone,

12:57.985 --> 13:00.988
{\an1}but mid-year,
it'll be tough.

13:01.071 --> 13:02.364
Well, you'll be
back, won't you?

13:02.448 --> 13:04.366
{\an3}I mean, how long is
this hearing gonna take?

13:04.450 --> 13:06.535
Brandon, I'm not supposed
to talk about it.

13:06.619 --> 13:08.037
That's all right, I'll just ask
you questions,

13:08.120 --> 13:09.038
you can nod your head yes or no,

13:09.121 --> 13:10.080
like in
<i>All The President's Men</i>

13:10.164 --> 13:11.957
You know, Woodward
and Bernstein?

13:12.041 --> 13:14.210
I'm gonna miss you guys a lot.

13:14.293 --> 13:15.961
You sound like you're giving up,

13:16.045 --> 13:17.546
{\an3}like you're leaving,
but at the hearing....

13:17.630 --> 13:19.757
Brandon, there's not gonna be
a hearing, because I <i> am</i> leaving.

13:19.840 --> 13:21.050
If I go quietly

13:21.133 --> 13:22.927
and don't fight it,
then Mrs...

13:23.010 --> 13:24.094
the girl's mother

13:24.178 --> 13:27.097
{\an1}will drop the matter
and they'll close the books.

13:27.181 --> 13:28.891
But why would you want
to do that?

13:28.974 --> 13:31.268
Why do you think?

13:31.352 --> 13:32.603
Come on, Gil, you gotta fight
this thing.

13:32.686 --> 13:33.646
You gotta clear your name.

13:33.729 --> 13:35.105
Brandon, I told you,
I don't wanna discuss it.

13:49.161 --> 13:52.081
Hi.

13:52.164 --> 13:55.876
{\an1}Hi. Um, I was just writing
a note,

13:55.960 --> 13:58.712
but I decided not to.

13:58.796 --> 14:00.881
Do you remember me?

14:00.965 --> 14:03.926
Uh, yeah, from the other night
at the Peach Pit.

14:04.009 --> 14:07.930
Right, and I was also out there
in the hall

14:08.013 --> 14:09.265
the other day.

14:09.348 --> 14:13.936
{\an3}You looked pretty upset
when you ran out of here.

14:14.019 --> 14:14.270
You're from the newspaper,
right?

14:14.353 --> 14:16.230
{\an3}Mm-hmm.

14:16.313 --> 14:18.774
But I'm not looking
for a story from you.

14:18.857 --> 14:19.984
Why not?

14:20.067 --> 14:21.151
I imagine you prefer

14:21.235 --> 14:22.778
to keep your personal
business private.

14:22.861 --> 14:25.281
Well, why do you care
what I prefer?

14:25.364 --> 14:27.658
Nobody else does.

14:27.741 --> 14:29.118
{\an3}Look, Sue,

14:29.201 --> 14:31.078
{\an3}I'm involved with something
called "peer counseling."

14:31.161 --> 14:32.079
I'm not interested.

14:32.162 --> 14:34.331
{\an3}Do you know
what it's about?

14:34.415 --> 14:36.125
{\an1}It's like having a kid
for a therapist!

14:36.208 --> 14:37.793
No, thanks!
It's not a therapist.

14:37.876 --> 14:39.587
{\an3}It's someone you
can talk to,

14:39.670 --> 14:41.589
{\an3}someone who can understand
how you're feeling.

14:41.672 --> 14:43.132
And how are you supposed
to understand how I feel?

14:43.215 --> 14:46.302
Because I once
had a teacher

14:46.385 --> 14:48.137
that I really cared for.

14:48.220 --> 14:53.142
{\an6}Someone I thought
I was falling
in love with.

14:53.225 --> 14:55.144
And what happened?

14:55.227 --> 14:57.438
Look, if I,
I tell you about this,

14:57.521 --> 14:58.522
I want us to have
an understanding.

14:58.606 --> 15:00.149
{\an3}I don't want to share
my feelings with everybody,

15:00.232 --> 15:02.151
just you.

15:02.234 --> 15:03.986
Well, I wouldn't tell anyone.

15:04.069 --> 15:06.155
And the same goes
for stuff you tell me,

15:06.238 --> 15:09.199
{\an3}okay?

15:09.283 --> 15:10.200
Okay.

15:10.284 --> 15:12.995
Good. Come on.

15:13.078 --> 15:15.080
(doorbell rings)

15:17.541 --> 15:18.167
{\an1}Andrea, hi.
Brandon's not here.

15:18.250 --> 15:19.209
Well, that's okay.

15:19.293 --> 15:21.045
Actually, I came by
to talk to you.

15:21.128 --> 15:23.172
I was hoping I could ask you
some questions.

15:23.255 --> 15:25.966
Step into my office.

15:29.762 --> 15:31.847
But why are you so interested
in Sue?

15:31.930 --> 15:33.599
Is it because
of Gil Meyers?

15:33.682 --> 15:34.725
How did you know

15:34.808 --> 15:35.893
Sue was involved?

15:35.976 --> 15:36.852
Well, it's all over
school by now.

15:36.935 --> 15:38.020
{\an3}I mean, you can't keep
that kind of thing

15:38.103 --> 15:39.063
a secret for very long.

15:39.146 --> 15:40.147
Well, you were her senior buddy.

15:40.230 --> 15:41.190
What's the story with her?

15:41.273 --> 15:43.942
Well, according to Donna,

15:44.026 --> 15:46.487
the Scanlon family never really
recovered from Scott's death.

15:46.570 --> 15:49.490
{\an6}Sue's dad just kind
of checked out of
it emotionally.

15:49.573 --> 15:51.992
And her mom
is a major control freak.

15:52.076 --> 15:54.161
So, she's just kind
of an innocent victim

15:54.244 --> 15:55.746
in all this.

15:55.829 --> 15:58.666
Well, with the way that she came
on to David at the Pigskin Prom,

15:58.749 --> 16:00.501
I don't think you can really
call her "innocent".

16:00.584 --> 16:02.336
Brenda, get ready for this one!

16:02.419 --> 16:03.712
You'll be interested
in this, too.

16:03.796 --> 16:08.092
I found out who accused
Mr. Meyers: Sue Scanlon.

16:09.343 --> 16:13.722
This is not news to you.

16:13.806 --> 16:15.933
I'm always the last to know.

16:16.016 --> 16:18.018
How come you're so chipper?

16:18.102 --> 16:19.144
Well, I couldn't figure out

16:19.228 --> 16:21.063
why a mother would just let
a sex offender walk away

16:21.146 --> 16:23.232
unless she knew the charges
were totally bogus.

16:23.315 --> 16:26.735
And now that we find out who
the so-called "victim" is,

16:26.819 --> 16:27.736
it all makes sense.

16:27.820 --> 16:29.738
Wait a minute!

16:29.822 --> 16:31.782
What makes you think

16:31.865 --> 16:32.908
{\an1}that Sue's not telling
the truth?

16:32.991 --> 16:34.702
Gil did not deny the
accusations, did he?

16:34.785 --> 16:35.911
That's because he can't.

16:35.994 --> 16:37.162
That's part
of their little deal.

16:37.246 --> 16:41.083
Brandon, are you aware there has
never been an unfounded claim

16:41.166 --> 16:42.918
of sexual abuse
at West Beverly High?

16:43.001 --> 16:45.546
Well, that doesn't mean
there can never be one.

16:45.629 --> 16:47.089
And this girl is a nut, right?

16:47.172 --> 16:48.340
Well, let's just say
she's troubled.

16:50.342 --> 16:51.135
You are doing

16:51.218 --> 16:54.096
exactly what society
has done to women

16:54.179 --> 16:55.097
for centuries;
you are blaming the victim.

16:55.180 --> 16:57.266
She should not be on trial!

16:57.349 --> 17:00.477
And what about being innocent
until proven guilty, huh?!

17:00.561 --> 17:02.771
He should have the right
to confront his accuser!

17:02.855 --> 17:04.189
Excuse me,
he does have that right

17:04.272 --> 17:06.900
and he's just chosen
not to exercise it.

17:06.983 --> 17:07.943
There's a difference.

17:08.026 --> 17:09.444
{\an3}That's because Mrs.
Scanlon's pressuring him!

17:09.528 --> 17:10.279
Or maybe it's because
he's not innocent.

17:10.362 --> 17:12.406
Have you thought of that?

17:14.074 --> 17:16.076
Look, the only reason
that you wanna believe Gil

17:16.160 --> 17:17.286
is because he's the guy,
and you can relate to that.

17:17.368 --> 17:21.290
Yeah, okay, I like to think
Gil and I have a lot in common.

17:21.373 --> 17:24.001
But what you and Sue have
in common, that is beyond me!

17:24.084 --> 17:26.502
Yeah, I guess it is.

17:28.881 --> 17:30.132
Good night, Brenda.

17:37.347 --> 17:41.977
Well, I think Andrea will accept
your apology... eventually.

17:42.060 --> 17:44.062
So, you think she's right
about Gil?

17:44.146 --> 17:45.814
Brandon, I don't know.

17:45.898 --> 17:48.901
I mean, I'm sure Sue is capable
of telling a few lies

17:48.984 --> 17:49.401
here and there,

17:49.485 --> 17:51.195
but I don't think

17:51.278 --> 17:52.279
{\an3}she would hurt Gil
for no reason.

17:52.362 --> 17:55.866
Oh, come on, Bren,
clearly, the girl is screwed up.

17:55.949 --> 17:57.326
(doorbell rings)

17:57.409 --> 17:59.745
{\an1}It's probably Andrea coming
back to apologize to me.

18:03.040 --> 18:04.958
What are you doing here?

18:05.042 --> 18:06.668
Uh, it's a guy thing.

18:06.752 --> 18:09.254
{\an3}(chuckles):
David, I completely forgot.

18:09.338 --> 18:11.799
Oh, well, I didn't,
so, uh, let's do it.

18:11.882 --> 18:14.176
I can't.

18:14.259 --> 18:14.718
I've been working

18:14.802 --> 18:16.470
really hard at school,

18:16.553 --> 18:18.138
and, and with Meyers gone,
the paper's crazy.

18:18.222 --> 18:19.264
It's just not a good night.

18:19.348 --> 18:22.392
Brandon, we're going
to Kingston 12 tomorrow.

18:24.394 --> 18:27.189
How am I supposed
to go to a club

18:27.272 --> 18:28.148
and have a good time

18:28.232 --> 18:30.067
when our school
is in total upheaval, huh?

18:30.150 --> 18:31.360
Oh, please.

18:31.443 --> 18:35.656
And here I wasted
a great alibi on Donna.

18:35.739 --> 18:38.534
Oh, well, can't say
I didn't try.

18:38.617 --> 18:40.536
See you guys around.

18:40.619 --> 18:42.204
Sorry, David.

18:43.831 --> 18:46.083
{\an1}Bren, you won't tell anyone
David Silver came over

18:46.166 --> 18:47.835
{\an1}to give me dancing lessons,
will you?

18:47.918 --> 18:48.919
Oh, on one condition.

18:49.002 --> 18:51.004
{\an3}You actually have
to go to that dance club.

18:51.088 --> 18:51.672
Bren, I'm not....

18:51.755 --> 18:52.381
Brandon, isn't it about time

18:52.464 --> 18:53.131
you dropped this "I am what I am

18:53.215 --> 18:54.383
and I can't change" lame
attitude,

18:54.466 --> 18:57.594
and realize that you have a very
nice, very sexy girlfriend

18:57.678 --> 18:58.428
who wants to dance with you?

18:58.512 --> 19:01.932
{\an3}In other words,
don't blow this one.

19:28.792 --> 19:29.585
Working weekends, Zuckerman?

19:29.668 --> 19:32.254
{\an1}I just don't like leaving
any loose ends.

19:32.337 --> 19:35.465
I just came to pick up
some of my things.

19:35.549 --> 19:39.386
I can't believe you took
advantage of a girl

19:39.469 --> 19:41.305
just because
she had a crush on you.

19:41.388 --> 19:42.431
Excuse me?

19:42.514 --> 19:45.100
I know what happened.

19:45.183 --> 19:46.894
I know who was involved.

19:46.977 --> 19:50.397
{\an1}I saw her running out
of your classroom on Monday.

19:50.480 --> 19:51.481
For what it's worth,
I want you to know

19:51.565 --> 19:55.444
that I did not abuse
or make a pass at that girl.

19:55.527 --> 19:58.447
I don't know how you define
the word "abuse".

19:58.530 --> 20:01.325
{\an4}All I know
is that she was hurt
and you were the cause.

20:01.408 --> 20:03.452
I was trying to help her.

20:03.535 --> 20:08.457
Do you really have
so little faith in me?

20:08.540 --> 20:11.543
Kids just don't make up
these things.

20:14.546 --> 20:16.798
{\an1}You're not even putting up
a defense!

20:16.882 --> 20:17.841
You're just running away.

20:17.925 --> 20:19.635
{\an1}Andrea, the reason
I'm taking that deal

20:19.718 --> 20:20.469
{\an1}is that I think
Sue is in trouble.

20:20.552 --> 20:23.013
I don't think she can handle

20:23.096 --> 20:23.722
a confrontational hearing
right now.

20:23.805 --> 20:26.683
Oh, so you're just being noble?

20:26.767 --> 20:30.145
You, you're protecting her
even though you know

20:30.228 --> 20:31.438
{\an3}your whole teaching
career is on the line?

20:31.521 --> 20:33.941
At least if I leave
on their terms,

20:34.024 --> 20:36.276
I might still have
a teaching career.

20:36.360 --> 20:37.486
I know I can do
a lot of other things,

20:37.569 --> 20:42.032
but I just happen to like
working with young people.

20:42.115 --> 20:43.492
Maybe you like it
a little too much.

20:43.575 --> 20:46.453
Maybe I do,
but I can live with that.

20:46.536 --> 20:49.331
What I cannot live with
is having two suicides

20:49.414 --> 20:50.374
on my conscience
for the rest of my life.

20:50.457 --> 20:52.751
What do you mean?

20:59.549 --> 21:01.551
On my first teaching job,
there was a girl...

21:01.635 --> 21:04.846
a very troubled girl,

21:04.930 --> 21:11.687
but she was very bright,
beautiful, an amazing girl.

21:11.770 --> 21:17.484
She fell in love with me, but I
did what I was supposed to do.

21:17.567 --> 21:19.861
I held the line.

21:19.945 --> 21:22.614
I even pushed her away.

21:22.698 --> 21:26.618
I was very clear,
and she killed herself.

21:31.248 --> 21:31.790
Because of you?

21:31.873 --> 21:35.252
That's what the note said.

21:37.838 --> 21:38.797
So you see, Andrea,

21:38.880 --> 21:41.591
{\an1}I am not about to publicly
call Sue Scanlon a liar.

21:41.675 --> 21:45.554
{\an1}As long as I know the truth,
that's all that matters.

21:45.637 --> 21:47.514
{\an3}For you, but
what about for her?

21:47.597 --> 21:52.436
I think I'm just about
the last person

21:52.519 --> 21:53.520
that can help her right now.

21:53.603 --> 21:56.398
If you want
to take a stab at it,

21:56.481 --> 21:57.858
be my guest.

22:06.658 --> 22:08.201
{\an5}GIL:
Well, if it isn't
the birthday boy.

22:08.285 --> 22:08.952
DYLAN:
Hey, how are ya?

22:09.036 --> 22:10.829
{\an1}How come you're
landlocked today?

22:10.912 --> 22:12.581
Oh, it's my doctor.

22:12.664 --> 22:17.085
She said that the water quality
is detrimental to my health.

22:17.169 --> 22:18.879
It's a shame, isn't it?

22:18.962 --> 22:20.088
Oh, man, it's a travesty.

22:20.172 --> 22:21.631
I mean, here we have this
beautiful natural resource

22:21.715 --> 22:24.593
{\an3}and we're turning it
into a trash heap!

22:24.676 --> 22:25.844
You sound motivated.

22:25.927 --> 22:29.389
You know, Friends of the Bay
can always use more volunteers.

22:29.473 --> 22:30.599
That's a good
organization.

22:30.682 --> 22:32.976
{\an3}I'll probably
check them out.

22:33.060 --> 22:36.271
So, uh, how's it
going with you?

22:36.354 --> 22:40.108
Ah, up and down, you know.

22:40.192 --> 22:41.651
{\an3}Listen, I, I don't even
know what happened,

22:41.735 --> 22:44.905
{\an3}and I don't usually ask
these kinds of questions,

22:44.988 --> 22:47.783
{\an3}but I was talking
to Brandon, and he told me.

22:47.866 --> 22:49.951
I gotta tell you,
if it were me...

22:50.035 --> 22:51.745
{\an3}if I were accused
of something I didn't do,

22:51.828 --> 22:53.580
{\an3}I'd be out of here, man--
no explanations, no defense.

22:53.663 --> 22:55.624
Nothing, I'm gone.

22:55.707 --> 22:58.126
Thanks, Dylan.

22:58.210 --> 23:02.089
{\an1}But you know, some things
just aren't black and white.

23:02.172 --> 23:04.132
{\an3}Yeah, well, I wasn't
there, so....

23:04.216 --> 23:07.302
{\an1}I mean, if that girl
got the wrong message,

23:07.385 --> 23:08.929
maybe it was my fault.

23:09.012 --> 23:10.472
I don't know, man.

23:10.555 --> 23:12.891
{\an3}You can always
second-guess yourself.

23:12.974 --> 23:15.769
{\an3}You know,
hindsight's 20/20.

23:15.852 --> 23:16.603
Maybe so.

23:16.686 --> 23:18.688
So what are you gonna do?

23:18.772 --> 23:19.689
(laughing)

23:19.773 --> 23:21.566
You got any suggestions?

23:24.361 --> 23:25.987
