26:12.904 --> 26:14.155
get to meet you
the other day.

26:14.239 --> 26:16.616
{\an3}So she wanted me to
invite you over tonight

26:16.700 --> 26:18.410
{\an3}for dinner.
Tonight?

26:18.493 --> 26:20.036
Please?

26:20.120 --> 26:20.829
Sure.

26:20.912 --> 26:23.290
Okay, I'll see you later.

26:28.169 --> 26:30.672
{\an3}Say, Brandon, did you
and Nikki ever make up?

26:30.755 --> 26:32.841
{\an1}I don't believe I've made up
with you yet, Steve.

26:32.924 --> 26:34.801
Aw, come on.

26:34.884 --> 26:36.219
{\an3}I was just trying to
get you off your rump.

26:36.303 --> 26:37.679
Uh-huh, and who asked you?

26:37.762 --> 26:39.681
I'll tell you what,

26:39.764 --> 26:42.183
{\an3}if you and Nikki
ever break up,

26:42.267 --> 26:44.185
you let me know, okay?

26:44.269 --> 26:44.728
God.

26:56.740 --> 26:58.408
Hey, Nikki, um...

26:58.491 --> 26:59.826
if you're willing to talk,

26:59.909 --> 27:02.704
{\an1}I just want to
tell you I'm sorry.

27:02.787 --> 27:03.913
For what?

27:03.997 --> 27:07.709
{\an3}Telling me off, or
not dancing with me?

27:07.792 --> 27:10.712
Both.

27:10.795 --> 27:13.048
{\an5}Look, Brandon,
I just think in
a relationship,

27:13.131 --> 27:14.924
{\an3}there's some differences
you can live with

27:15.008 --> 27:15.925
and some you can't.

27:16.009 --> 27:19.387
{\an1}And how do you know so much
about relationships?

27:19.471 --> 27:20.722
Because I'm a girl.

27:20.805 --> 27:21.890
And that's what girls do.

27:21.973 --> 27:25.518
Mm.

27:25.602 --> 27:29.105
{\an3}So do we get to kiss
and make up now?

27:29.189 --> 27:32.400
{\an1}It's not going to be
that easy.

27:32.484 --> 27:34.694
There's still the issue:

27:34.778 --> 27:37.280
one dances and the
other one doesn't.

27:37.364 --> 27:38.865
What do you want
me to do, Nikki?

27:38.948 --> 27:41.993
{\an3}I have no rhythm,
end of story.

27:42.994 --> 27:44.954
Okay.

27:45.038 --> 27:46.915
How 'bout this?

27:46.998 --> 27:49.167
One private dance lesson.

27:49.250 --> 27:50.710
Your home turf.

27:50.794 --> 27:52.087
Your favorite music.

27:52.170 --> 27:55.757
{\an1}Your favorite
dance instructor.

27:55.840 --> 27:57.717
{\an1}You give it your all
one time,

27:57.801 --> 27:59.302
just, just one time,

27:59.386 --> 27:59.969
and if you truly
have no rhythm,

28:00.053 --> 28:02.680
{\an1}I will never
complain again.

28:03.932 --> 28:06.559
All right, you got a deal.

28:07.894 --> 28:09.270
You want half my sandwich?

28:09.354 --> 28:11.231
Oh, no thanks.

28:11.314 --> 28:12.899
{\an1}I think you've lost about
five pounds in the last week.

28:12.982 --> 28:16.111
Yeah, well, it's called
learning the hard way.

28:16.194 --> 28:18.738
What's the Coastal
Waters Initiative?

28:18.822 --> 28:19.948
{\an3}It's a measure on
the ballot this year.

28:20.031 --> 28:22.951
{\an3}The people down at Friends
of the Bay turned me on to it,

28:23.034 --> 28:25.120
{\an3}seeing as how I've reached
the age of majority.

28:25.203 --> 28:27.789
{\an1}You get to vote for it.
How cool.

28:27.872 --> 28:29.290
{\an3}All I gotta do is register.
I'm pretty stoked.

28:29.374 --> 28:30.792
I'm bummed!

28:30.875 --> 28:32.794
How incredibly unfair.

28:32.877 --> 28:34.712
Who would've known
you had to register

28:34.796 --> 28:36.131
30 days before
the election?

28:36.214 --> 28:37.966
Anyone who'd read this
information pamphlet.

28:38.049 --> 28:39.467
I'm sorry.

28:39.551 --> 28:40.802
{\an1}So am I.

28:40.885 --> 28:42.846
{\an3}I'll just have to try
and cheer you up.

28:42.929 --> 28:44.347
Better not.

28:44.431 --> 28:46.599
{\an1}Doc Littman says I might
still be contagious.

28:46.683 --> 28:48.017
{\an1}Ooh, bummer.
Yeah.

28:53.523 --> 28:54.941
Hi.

28:58.069 --> 29:00.321
{\an1}I'm sorry.
You shouldn't come in.

29:00.405 --> 29:01.364
What's the matter?

29:01.448 --> 29:05.827
I know I invited you over,
but I made a mistake.

29:07.704 --> 29:09.164
Oh, that's okay.
Don't worry about it.

29:09.247 --> 29:10.832
Sue, what are you...?

29:10.915 --> 29:13.001
Oh, hi, you must be Andrea.

29:13.084 --> 29:16.838
I'm so happy to meet you.
Come in.

29:19.966 --> 29:24.721
{\an1}Henry, I'd like you
to meet someone.

29:24.804 --> 29:25.096
This is Andrea Zookerman.

29:25.180 --> 29:26.848
Zuckerman.

29:26.931 --> 29:27.891
{\an1}Zuckerman.

29:27.974 --> 29:29.017
{\an4}Uh, uh, this is
my brother, Henry.
Hi.

29:29.100 --> 29:32.645
We knew a Zuckerman family
in Oklahoma City.

29:32.729 --> 29:33.980
I believe they were mortgage
brokers, any relation?

29:34.063 --> 29:35.899
I don't think so.

29:35.982 --> 29:37.358
{\an3}I've never been
to Oklahoma before.

29:37.442 --> 29:39.194
{\an1}Sue's spent the last five
summers in Oklahoma.

29:39.277 --> 29:41.362
{\an3}Uh, we're gonna
go upstairs.

29:41.446 --> 29:42.572
No, you're not.

29:42.655 --> 29:44.324
{\an1}We're gonna start
eating soon.

29:44.407 --> 29:45.200
{\an1}Did you know
that Sue's friend

29:45.283 --> 29:47.869
is the smartest girl
in West Beverly High,

29:47.952 --> 29:50.163
{\an1}and she is going
to Yale next year?

29:50.246 --> 29:52.207
{\an3}I'm not the smartest,
believe me,

29:52.290 --> 29:53.082
{\an3}and I've just applied
to Yale; I didn't get...

29:53.166 --> 29:55.835
And she is the editor
of the school paper.

29:55.919 --> 29:57.504
Editor-in-chief?

29:57.587 --> 29:58.505
Is that right?

29:58.588 --> 30:00.006
{\an3}Well, actually, this year
I'm the co-editor.

30:00.089 --> 30:01.049
Maybe Sue could do some
writing for the paper.

30:01.132 --> 30:02.926
{\an3}Well, sure,
if she'd like to.

30:03.009 --> 30:06.095
You know, I used to write
for my high school paper.

30:06.179 --> 30:07.847
Did you really?
Susan,

30:07.931 --> 30:08.890
{\an1}get your brothers
and sisters.

30:08.973 --> 30:11.392
We're gonna start dinner.

30:11.476 --> 30:13.061
Trouble was, if I didn't
have a good story,

30:13.144 --> 30:16.898
well, I'd just make one up.

30:16.981 --> 30:19.567
{\an3}(laughs)

30:19.651 --> 30:20.902
Ah, such a kidder.

30:20.985 --> 30:23.404
NIKKI:
<i>Brandon, no one will</i>

30:23.488 --> 30:24.656
see you.

30:24.739 --> 30:26.908
Nobody's home.

30:26.991 --> 30:29.244
The doors are locked.

30:29.327 --> 30:31.704
{\an1}I tell you what,
I'll even turn my back.

30:31.788 --> 30:33.081
(music playing)

30:33.164 --> 30:35.083
You did agree to this.
I did?

30:35.166 --> 30:36.417
Yes, you did.

30:36.501 --> 30:38.253
Now come on.

30:38.336 --> 30:39.087
{\an1}Come on, Brandon.
Just loosen up.

30:39.170 --> 30:41.548
Uh, start with
the feet first.

30:41.631 --> 30:42.924
Don't even worry
about the hands.

30:43.007 --> 30:46.553
You follow me, Brandon.

30:47.720 --> 30:49.097
Brandon!

30:49.180 --> 30:50.723
That's not what
I call giving it your all.

30:50.807 --> 30:52.267
{\an1}You're not giving it
your anything.

30:52.350 --> 30:55.270
Well, you see that music
just wasn't quite right.

30:55.353 --> 30:58.356
{\an3}Now this music
I like much better.

30:58.439 --> 30:59.107
(ballad plays)

30:59.190 --> 31:01.776
You want to slow dance?

31:01.859 --> 31:03.236
Yeah, any objections?

31:03.319 --> 31:04.946
No, not at all.

31:05.029 --> 31:06.489
{\an3}Good, 'cause I know
this one dance.

31:06.573 --> 31:07.907
You may have heard of it.

31:07.991 --> 31:10.618
{\an3}It's called the,
uh, Brandon Waltz.

31:10.702 --> 31:13.621
No, no, I haven't heard of it.

31:13.705 --> 31:16.874
I guess you're gonna
have to teach me.

31:18.126 --> 31:24.591
♪ If you haven't heard
the latest news ♪

31:24.674 --> 31:28.928
♪ I want to know if you feel
the same 'bout me, too ♪

31:29.012 --> 31:30.597
♪<i> Heavy on my mind</i> ♪

31:30.680 --> 31:31.931
♪ Heavy on my mind ♪

31:32.015 --> 31:33.808
♪<i> Spending all my time</i> ♪

31:33.891 --> 31:35.977
♪ Spending all my time ♪

31:36.060 --> 31:38.354
Can I take your plate?
Sure, honey.

31:38.438 --> 31:39.564
{\an3}Thank you.

31:39.647 --> 31:41.816
{\an4}ANDREA:
Thank you for dinner,
Mrs. Scanlon. It was great.

31:41.899 --> 31:42.984
{\an1}Oh, you'll have to come
again soon sometime

31:43.067 --> 31:45.778
when Conrad isn't
away on business.

31:45.862 --> 31:48.698
{\an1}But thank heavens we have
Henry here filling in,

31:48.781 --> 31:51.701
guarding the homestead.

31:51.784 --> 31:53.661
{\an1}Why don't we put on
a videotape of the ranch.

31:53.745 --> 31:55.121
{\an4}Then you can see...
You know, I don't think
she's at all interested

31:55.204 --> 31:56.331
in our home movies, Mother.

31:56.414 --> 31:58.708
But we have those
terrific horse shows,

31:58.791 --> 31:59.542
and we have Scotty jumping...

31:59.626 --> 32:01.169
I don't want to see
Scotty jumping.

32:01.252 --> 32:03.212
Scotty is dead.

32:06.924 --> 32:09.969
I have to apologize
for my daughter.

32:11.596 --> 32:12.430
She hasn't been herself
since that...

32:12.513 --> 32:15.850
nasty mess with
that disgusting teacher.

32:15.933 --> 32:18.311
{\an1}Do you have to keep
talking about it?

32:18.394 --> 32:21.022
{\an3}It seems to me
that you were the one

32:21.105 --> 32:22.899
{\an3}who talked about it first,
weren't you, Sue?

32:25.109 --> 32:26.194
Yes, I was.

32:26.277 --> 32:27.236
So if you started it,

32:27.320 --> 32:29.864
well, then you ought
to finish it,

32:29.947 --> 32:30.865
{\an3}don't you think?
Henry...

32:30.948 --> 32:32.742
I'm sorry, but I don't believe

32:32.825 --> 32:35.536
I ever got a clear explanation
of exactly what that whole

32:35.620 --> 32:36.746
{\an3}nasty mess
was all about.

32:36.829 --> 32:37.789
Henry, for heaven's sake.

32:37.872 --> 32:40.833
All I've heard's a lot of talk

32:40.917 --> 32:41.626
{\an3}about how he tried
to seduce her,

32:41.709 --> 32:43.628
{\an3}tried to have
his way with her.

32:45.213 --> 32:47.757
I want to know exactly
what's she's saying he did.

32:49.092 --> 32:50.551
And what she did
to make him think

32:50.635 --> 32:51.719
he could make
such advances.

32:51.803 --> 32:54.222
What are you talking about?
Sue didn't do anything.

32:54.305 --> 32:56.099
Is that right, Sue?

32:56.182 --> 32:59.894
You didn't do
anything, huh?

32:59.977 --> 33:02.230
No.

33:02.313 --> 33:03.314
No, that's not right at all.

33:10.154 --> 33:11.948
I was the one who tried
to seduce him.

33:12.031 --> 33:13.950
Susan!
It's true.

33:19.497 --> 33:21.708
I tried to kiss him,

33:21.791 --> 33:23.376
but he wouldn't let me.

33:25.002 --> 33:26.254
It was me!

33:31.718 --> 33:33.010
(door slams)

33:42.186 --> 33:45.398
So, on behalf of
the entire <i> Blaze</i> staff,

33:45.481 --> 33:47.275
AP English
and everybody else here,

33:47.358 --> 33:48.109
we know this has been
a big ordeal for you, man.

33:48.192 --> 33:49.318
It's good to have you back.

33:49.402 --> 33:53.072
(applause)

33:53.156 --> 33:54.407
{\an1}Thanks for the
support, you guys.

33:54.490 --> 33:55.783
No sweat, man.

33:55.867 --> 33:57.952
I don't think my brother
ever would've gotten over it

33:58.035 --> 33:59.454
if you'd really left.

33:59.537 --> 34:01.164
{\an1}Then it's a good thing
I didn't have to.

34:01.247 --> 34:04.208
I gotta go. I told Mrs. Teasley
I'd be right back.

34:05.710 --> 34:07.295
{\an1}Brandon, I just want
to say, for once,

34:07.378 --> 34:10.965
{\an1}I'm, uh, I'm glad
I was wrong.

34:11.047 --> 34:12.300
Yeah, me, too, Chief.

34:14.217 --> 34:17.013
So are you done
being sick now?

34:17.096 --> 34:17.304
I think so.

34:17.388 --> 34:18.264
Good.

34:18.347 --> 34:20.600
Why?

34:20.683 --> 34:22.143
{\an1}You worried
about me, Kelly?

34:22.226 --> 34:24.228
Hey, what are
friends for?

34:32.862 --> 34:35.322
Listen. I'm... I'm sorry

34:35.406 --> 34:36.324
I jumped to conclusions.

34:36.407 --> 34:38.784
Don't apologize.

34:38.868 --> 34:40.828
You gave me a lot
of food for thought.

34:40.911 --> 34:43.748
Well, at least
you cleared your name.

34:45.833 --> 34:46.667
Yeah, I guess.

34:46.751 --> 34:48.377
You're thinking about Sue,
aren't you?

34:48.460 --> 34:50.797
It's hard not to.

34:50.880 --> 34:52.340
How's she doing?

34:52.422 --> 34:53.841
I don't know.

34:53.925 --> 34:54.842
Her mother's keeping her
in seclusion.

34:54.926 --> 34:57.553
I was planning to drop
by her house later.

34:57.637 --> 35:00.348
If you can help her, whatever
you can do, it'd be great.

35:01.307 --> 35:03.976
(doorbell ringing)

35:04.060 --> 35:06.020
Hi, Mrs. Scanlon.

35:06.103 --> 35:07.230
Is, uh, Sue home?

35:07.313 --> 35:10.817
Sue isn't seeing anyone
but family right now.

35:10.900 --> 35:12.610
{\an1}Sorry.

35:12.693 --> 35:15.404
I just thought that
maybe you could just....

35:18.115 --> 35:19.534
Yeah, but you're
her senior buddy.

35:19.617 --> 35:21.869
{\an3}Look, that's not gonna get me
very far in that household.

35:21.953 --> 35:23.538
{\an1}She shouldn't
be so isolated.

35:23.621 --> 35:25.540
{\an1}I mean, who knows
what she's thinking?

35:25.623 --> 35:28.960
She's probably feeling very
guilty and depressed right now.

35:29.043 --> 35:31.087
{\an1}Well, being shut up
in that house

35:31.170 --> 35:32.380
{\an1}cannot improve
her mental health.

35:32.463 --> 35:34.549
{\an1}That has got to be one
of the spookiest families

35:34.632 --> 35:36.217
{\an1}I've ever been
in contact with.

35:36.300 --> 35:38.219
{\an3}Look, I know, but
what can we do?

35:38.302 --> 35:39.554
(sighs)

35:39.637 --> 35:41.472
Somebody's gotta get in there.

35:43.808 --> 35:46.894
{\an3}And I think I know someone
who has the best chance.

35:46.978 --> 35:47.562
Who?

35:47.645 --> 35:49.605
Don't look at me like that.

35:49.689 --> 35:51.858
Please, Donna. We think
this is a really critical time.

35:51.941 --> 35:54.527
{\an1}Look, Sue hasn't been
in school for days,

35:54.610 --> 35:56.529
and you know how self-
destructive she can be.

35:56.612 --> 35:57.864
Well, what can <i> I</i> do?

35:57.947 --> 35:59.073
You can be her
friend, Donna.

35:59.156 --> 36:01.075
{\an3}She probably thinks
she doesn't have any left.

36:01.158 --> 36:04.161
Well, you don't think
she'd do anything major, do you?

36:04.245 --> 36:05.413
Look, there's
no way to know

36:05.496 --> 36:07.790
if she's suicidal unless we
get in there to talk to her.

36:07.874 --> 36:09.083
But you said yourself

36:09.166 --> 36:10.918
Mrs. Scanlon would not
let anybody in.

36:11.002 --> 36:12.086
Only family.

36:12.170 --> 36:14.338
Well, I'm not exactly considered
a member of the family.

36:14.422 --> 36:16.424
No, but your
boyfriend <i> is.</i>

36:21.345 --> 36:24.265
How did I let myself
get talked into this?

36:24.348 --> 36:26.100
'Cause you care about Sue

36:26.183 --> 36:28.561
{\an6}and you know that Scott
would've wanted you
to look after her.

36:28.644 --> 36:30.771
{\an1}Well, don't you think this
calls for professional help?

36:30.855 --> 36:32.940
Well, maybe it's not
as bad as we think.

36:33.024 --> 36:34.775
{\an3}I mean, Mrs. Scanlon sounded
thrilled to hear from you.

36:34.859 --> 36:35.776
Yeah, well,

36:35.860 --> 36:37.236
any time
Mrs. Scanlon's thrilled,

36:37.320 --> 36:39.071
(doorbell ringing)
you know it's a bad sign.

36:43.409 --> 36:46.829
David! Hi. Um...

36:46.913 --> 36:48.289
Come on in, you guys.

36:48.372 --> 36:48.789
My mom is gonna be

36:48.873 --> 36:50.291
so happy you're here.

36:50.374 --> 36:52.919
David! Oh...

36:53.002 --> 36:55.546
You have gotten so tall now.

36:55.630 --> 36:59.091
Somehow I still expected you
to come up just to my chin.

36:59.175 --> 37:00.676
Yeah, I just kept on growing.

37:00.760 --> 37:03.095
Luckily Donna
sort of leveled off.

37:03.387 --> 37:05.348
Sue, you look good.
How are you feeling?

37:05.431 --> 37:07.808
Fine. How are you?

37:07.892 --> 37:09.477
Sue, go tell Uncle Henry to put
some more meat on the grill.

37:09.560 --> 37:11.604
No, that's okay.

37:11.687 --> 37:12.813
No, no, no, no, no.

37:12.897 --> 37:15.608
{\an1}We're having a barbecue
and you have to stay.

37:15.691 --> 37:17.443
Well, actually,
we were just worried

37:17.526 --> 37:18.819
because Sue wasn't in school.

37:18.903 --> 37:20.112
Yes, well, that school.

37:20.196 --> 37:21.030
That was the problem.

37:21.113 --> 37:23.616
You kids are almost
finished, thank God,

37:23.699 --> 37:25.993
but the thought
of four more years?

37:26.077 --> 37:27.662
Sue would not have survived it.

37:27.745 --> 37:29.038
(chopping)

37:29.121 --> 37:30.831
{\an1}You mean, you're pulling her
out of West Beverly?

37:30.915 --> 37:32.083
Absolutely.

37:32.166 --> 37:32.500
{\an3}Well, where's
she going to go?

37:32.583 --> 37:36.003
We're moving.

37:36.087 --> 37:37.171
We just decided.

37:37.254 --> 37:38.965
{\an1}Conrad is looking
at houses

37:39.048 --> 37:41.801
right now in Oklahoma
near my family.

37:41.884 --> 37:43.511
Oklahoma?

37:43.594 --> 37:45.221
The children need
a healthier environment.

37:45.304 --> 37:46.514
That's all there is to it.

37:46.597 --> 37:48.557
Imagine this:
fresh air, no traffic,

37:48.641 --> 37:52.812
{\an1}a community with
wholesome family values?

37:52.895 --> 37:54.522
And Conrad is
on the road so much

37:54.605 --> 37:56.315
it doesn't matter
where <i> he's</i> based.

37:56.399 --> 37:58.442
{\an1}Well, don't you think that's
kind of a sudden decision?

38:01.278 --> 38:04.073
Oh, it's not gonna be easy
to leave this house, believe me.

38:04.156 --> 38:06.867
All the happy times
that we've had here,

38:06.951 --> 38:09.870
{\an1}and you've been here to share
so many of them with us,

38:09.954 --> 38:13.874
all the big events...
and the milestones.

38:13.958 --> 38:17.378
Anyway, we are gonna have
a whole fresh start.

38:17.461 --> 38:19.755
So come on out
in the backyard

38:19.839 --> 38:22.675
{\an1}because we need
to celebrate.

38:22.758 --> 38:27.722
♪ If it's something real
to make... ♪

38:27.805 --> 38:29.682
Amy! Slow down!

38:31.142 --> 38:33.561
♪ If it's something strong... ♪

38:33.644 --> 38:35.062
David, what is going on?

38:35.146 --> 38:38.524
These people act like
everything is fine and dandy.

38:38.607 --> 38:40.609
{\an3}Well, the Scanlons
love barbecues.

38:44.613 --> 38:47.074
Um, Sue, can, can I talk
to you for a minute?

38:47.158 --> 38:48.743
Sure.

38:48.826 --> 38:50.745
Listen, I just,
I just wanted to make sure

38:50.828 --> 38:51.746
everything's all right.

38:51.829 --> 38:53.748
Well, why wouldn't it be?

38:53.831 --> 38:55.750
Well, I just thought,

38:55.833 --> 38:56.584
{\an1}with everything you've
been going through,

38:56.667 --> 39:00.254
{\an1}you might need
someone to talk to.

39:00.337 --> 39:01.422
{\an3}Well, what do
you care?

39:01.505 --> 39:03.424
I mean, really?

39:05.676 --> 39:07.553
{\an1}We were just worried.
That's all.

39:07.636 --> 39:08.804
I mean, Brenda,

39:08.888 --> 39:10.556
Andrea, even
Mr. Meyers.

39:10.639 --> 39:12.767
{\an3}Well, everything's
absolutely fine.

39:12.850 --> 39:15.102
I mean, I have my family.

39:15.186 --> 39:17.563
They're the ones who
really care about me.

39:17.646 --> 39:19.607
So you can just tell
everybody else to stop worrying.

39:19.690 --> 39:24.028
♪ In the lost and found... ♪

39:26.364 --> 39:27.573
{\an3}Well?

39:27.656 --> 39:29.575
I don't think I'm
very good at this.

39:29.658 --> 39:32.745
The more they say everything is
all right, the worse I feel.

39:32.828 --> 39:35.831
Do you kids want
hot dogs or hamburgers?

39:37.917 --> 39:39.960
♪ ♪

39:42.546 --> 39:45.508
{\an3}So, what's the deal
with Uncle Henry?

39:45.591 --> 39:48.427
Well, he was Scott's
favorite uncle,

39:48.511 --> 39:50.513
{\an1}but, uh, I guess last time
when he was in Oklahoma

39:50.596 --> 39:53.474
{\an1}something happened,
because he called him a jerk

39:53.557 --> 39:54.642
and never talked
about him again.

39:54.725 --> 39:55.810
{\an3}Good job.
Come on, Amy.

39:55.893 --> 39:57.144
You forgot to pick up
your stuff.

39:57.228 --> 39:59.230
Uncle Henry said
I didn't have to!

39:59.313 --> 40:00.815
{\an3}Sue.

40:00.898 --> 40:02.274
{\an3}When your father's
out of town,

40:02.358 --> 40:03.484
I'm in charge,
so don't think

40:03.567 --> 40:05.486
{\an3}that you can
call the shots.

40:05.569 --> 40:06.779
Come on, Amy.

40:10.116 --> 40:16.122
♪ If you don't let go,
it happens any day... ♪

40:20.251 --> 40:20.584
Sue?

40:23.754 --> 40:24.672
Hi.

40:24.755 --> 40:26.674
I was, uh...

40:26.757 --> 40:28.676
looking all over for you.

40:28.759 --> 40:30.553
{\an3}Well, I've
been <i> here.</i>

40:31.762 --> 40:34.682
Look, before we go,

40:34.765 --> 40:37.184
{\an1}I just, I wanted
you to know

40:37.268 --> 40:39.019
that I understand if you
don't feel like talking,

40:39.103 --> 40:40.813
{\an1}but if you change
your mind,

40:40.896 --> 40:42.982
you can call me any time.

40:43.065 --> 40:45.192
Or David.

40:45.276 --> 40:47.361
And I really do mean that.

40:47.444 --> 40:49.822
Well, what would we talk about?

40:52.741 --> 40:54.743
Whatever you want.

40:54.827 --> 40:58.038
{\an3}Are the kids at school
talking about me?

41:01.000 --> 41:03.544
I'm not gonna lie to you.

41:03.627 --> 41:06.005
They're curious about
what really happened.

41:06.088 --> 41:07.882
{\an1}And of course, it is
none of their business.

41:10.301 --> 41:11.802
I, uh...

41:11.886 --> 41:14.680
{\an1}I just keep thinking
about what Andrea said.

41:14.763 --> 41:16.182
What did Andrea say?

41:16.265 --> 41:20.060
{\an1}She said that kids just
don't make up stories abo...

41:20.978 --> 41:23.606
about...

41:23.689 --> 41:25.900
{\an1}well, that it
has to come

41:25.983 --> 41:26.692
from somewhere.

41:26.775 --> 41:27.735
{\an1}Anyway....

41:27.818 --> 41:29.945
{\an3}Do you want to know
what happened?

41:32.781 --> 41:34.867
I'll tell you
what happened.

41:37.036 --> 41:37.745
He was kissing me

41:37.828 --> 41:40.247
and touching me.

41:40.831 --> 41:43.751
I don't know who started it.

41:47.004 --> 41:48.422
It could have been me.

41:49.798 --> 41:53.427
He said it was me.

41:53.510 --> 41:55.721
But then I didn't want
to anymore...

41:57.723 --> 41:59.433
and I pulled away,

41:59.516 --> 42:03.229
but he wouldn't let me.

42:03.312 --> 42:04.772
He wouldn't let me go.

42:10.819 --> 42:12.988
He hurt me.

42:15.866 --> 42:18.786
If Mr. Meyers did this to you,
why'd you take it back?

42:18.869 --> 42:22.206
Because it wasn't Mr. Meyers.

42:22.289 --> 42:24.583
It wasn't him at all.

42:26.710 --> 42:28.295
It was my...

42:29.922 --> 42:32.091
It was my uncle.

42:35.552 --> 42:37.137
It's always been my uncle.

42:41.392 --> 42:42.101
(laughing)

42:42.184 --> 42:44.436
It's just not the
same city it was

42:44.520 --> 42:45.646
when we moved here,
not by a long shot.

42:45.729 --> 42:46.855
CHILD:
Come on, Terry!

42:46.939 --> 42:48.816
CHILD 2:
Yay!

42:48.899 --> 42:49.817
{\an1}Come on!

42:49.900 --> 42:51.026
Here we go.

42:57.032 --> 42:57.825
Mom, I need
to tell you something.

43:02.454 --> 43:03.956
What?

43:04.748 --> 43:06.667
You were right
after all, Andrea.

43:06.750 --> 43:08.794
Sue didn't make it up,

43:08.877 --> 43:10.838
{\an1}but I'm sure Mrs. Scanlon
never even suspected

43:10.921 --> 43:12.214
{\an1}that her brother
was a child abuser.

43:12.298 --> 43:13.215
Boy, he was smooth.

43:13.299 --> 43:14.842
And now I know why
Scott didn't like the guy.

43:14.925 --> 43:18.512
{\an1}So Sue was afraid he'd start
with the little sister?

43:18.596 --> 43:19.680
{\an1}I mean, how
unbelievably awful.

43:19.763 --> 43:22.725
{\an3}Well, at least Sue
doesn't have to carry

43:22.808 --> 43:25.185
the secret around
by herself anymore

43:25.269 --> 43:26.687
{\an3}and she can start
getting help.

43:26.770 --> 43:27.855
{\an1}DYLAN:
Hey, Bren!

43:27.938 --> 43:29.982
{\an3}Dylan!

43:30.065 --> 43:31.233
Guess what?

43:31.317 --> 43:32.735
Mmm.

43:32.818 --> 43:34.528
{\an5}Ah, you're not
contagious anymore.
That's right.

43:34.611 --> 43:36.780
So did you, uh,
break the bad news to Donna?

43:36.864 --> 43:38.699
What bad news?

43:38.782 --> 43:40.659
Well, you know how
you were looking forward

43:40.743 --> 43:42.369
to voting in the election?
It's too late.

43:42.453 --> 43:43.871
It is not. It's two weeks away.

43:43.954 --> 43:46.373
No, he means it's too late
to register to vote.

43:46.457 --> 43:47.583
So, I guess you guys are gonna

43:47.666 --> 43:49.251
have to sit this one out
with the rest of us.

43:49.335 --> 43:51.337
But I registered months ago.

43:51.420 --> 43:52.379
You did?

43:52.463 --> 43:53.756
Donna, I never thought
you were so civic-minded.

43:53.839 --> 43:54.882
Are you kidding?
I've been waiting

43:54.965 --> 43:57.343
my whole life
to vote for president.

43:57.426 --> 43:58.469
Way to go, Donna.

43:58.552 --> 44:00.137
So then, you are familiar

44:00.220 --> 44:00.721
with the Coastal Waters
Initiative?

44:00.804 --> 44:03.849
The what?

44:03.932 --> 44:06.018
Donna, allow me
to share with you

44:06.101 --> 44:08.145
my firsthand personal experience

44:08.228 --> 44:09.938
{\an3}with the hazards of
pollution in our seas.

44:10.022 --> 44:11.190
{\an3}Excuse me.

44:11.273 --> 44:12.191
Hey!
Hey, guys!

44:12.274 --> 44:13.359
{\an1}Hi.
Hey, Nat.

44:13.442 --> 44:14.526
You got something for me?

44:14.610 --> 44:15.903
{\an5}Ha-ha.
Here you go.
Thank you, sir.

44:15.986 --> 44:20.157
{\an3}And don't spend it all
in one place, right?

44:20.240 --> 44:21.784
Nikki, let's go.

44:21.867 --> 44:22.826
Where are you guys off to?

44:22.910 --> 44:23.786
We're gonna check out

44:23.869 --> 44:24.912
{\an1}the new dance club
on Robertson.

44:24.995 --> 44:27.498
See you guys.

44:27.581 --> 44:28.457
Bye.

44:28.540 --> 44:29.083
{\an1}Brandon.

44:29.166 --> 44:30.918
In a hurry to go dancing?

44:31.001 --> 44:32.878
Well, you see, David...
in a relationship,

44:32.961 --> 44:36.131
you learn important things
about the other person.

44:36.215 --> 44:39.927
For example, I have learned
how dancing makes Nikki feel.

44:40.010 --> 44:42.638
{\an3}And how <i> is</i>
that, Brandon?

44:42.888 --> 44:44.807
Romantic.

44:44.890 --> 44:46.934
{\an3}Bacteria are being
poured into our oceans

44:47.017 --> 44:50.104
and make you physically ill
to even go close to the water.

44:50.187 --> 44:52.439
{\an3}Just go.
Good-bye.

44:52.523 --> 44:53.941
{\an3}Good-bye.

44:54.024 --> 44:54.817
{\an1}Farewell.
So long.

44:54.900 --> 44:55.818
Good nighty.

44:55.901 --> 44:59.196
(chuckling)
